TY  - JOUR
T1  - What Can Explain Momentum? Evidence from Decomposition
AU  - Guo, Jiaqi
AU  - Li, Peng
AU  - Li, Youwei
Y1  - 2021/12/29
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4135
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4135
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6184
EP  - 6218
VL  - 68
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This study comprehensively evaluates and ranks a large number of competing explanations for the momentum anomaly. As a benchmark for evaluation, firm fundamentals are found to be the most promising among well-known explanations of momentum, followed by prospect theory and mental accounting, and anchoring effect. Collectively, all explanations capture 31% of momentum, whereas 69% of momentum remains unexplained. This study thoroughly examines what fractions of the momentum anomaly emerge from the interaction effects between past returns and various firm characteristics. It is further found that strategies based on firm characteristics and residual momentum can significantly alleviate the severity of momentum crashes. Finally, robustness analysis is provided for choosing different formation and holding periods, excluding January observations, and analyze at the level of portfolio rather than individual stock.This paper was accepted by David Simchi-Levi, finance.
AB  - This study comprehensively evaluates and ranks a large number of competing explanations for the momentum anomaly. As a benchmark for evaluation, firm fundamentals are found to be the most promising among well-known explanations of momentum, followed by prospect theory and mental accounting, and anchoring effect. Collectively, all explanations capture 31% of momentum, whereas 69% of momentum remains unexplained. This study thoroughly examines what fractions of the momentum anomaly emerge from the interaction effects between past returns and various firm characteristics. It is further found that strategies based on firm characteristics and residual momentum can significantly alleviate the severity of momentum crashes. Finally, robustness analysis is provided for choosing different formation and holding periods, excluding January observations, and analyze at the level of portfolio rather than individual stock.This paper was accepted by David Simchi-Levi, finance.
