T1  - The Willingness to Pay for Diversification
AU  - Mahmoud, Ola
Y1  - 2021/10/28
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2022/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4122
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2021.4122
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6235
EP  - 6249
VL  - 68
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Diversification is a fundamental concept in economics and finance. This paper argues that decision makers have an intrinsic preference for diversification that is responsive to cost and that this willingness to pay for diversification is driven by risk aversion and loss aversion. In an experiment replicating a portfolio choice problem, the value of diversification is estimated to be at 5% of the initial endowment of approximately $100. Moreover, risk-averse and loss-averse individuals are willing to pay more for diversification. These findings point to the idea that diversification is a fundamental preference and may help explain portfolio choice anomalies such as irrational diversification, the diversification bias, and overdiversification.This paper was accepted by Tomasz Piskorski, finance.
AB  - Diversification is a fundamental concept in economics and finance. This paper argues that decision makers have an intrinsic preference for diversification that is responsive to cost and that this willingness to pay for diversification is driven by risk aversion and loss aversion. In an experiment replicating a portfolio choice problem, the value of diversification is estimated to be at 5% of the initial endowment of approximately $100. Moreover, risk-averse and loss-averse individuals are willing to pay more for diversification. These findings point to the idea that diversification is a fundamental preference and may help explain portfolio choice anomalies such as irrational diversification, the diversification bias, and overdiversification.This paper was accepted by Tomasz Piskorski, finance.
