T1  - Beta-Delta or Delta-Tau? A Reformulation of Quasi-Hyperbolic Discounting
AU  - Bleichrodt, Han
AU  - Potter van Loon, Rogier J. D.
AU  - Prelec, Drazen
Y1  - 2022/06/07
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4453
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4453
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 6326
EP  - 6335
VL  - 68
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper introduces the index τ=ln?/lnδ as a measure of time inconsistency and vulnerability to self-control problems in the quasi-hyperbolic, beta-delta (?,δ) discounting model. We provide a preference foundation for τ and, consequently, a revealed preference definition of failed self-control. The τ index is independent of utility and has an intuitive interpretation as the maximum number of future selves who can disagree with the current self with respect to uniform deviations from an intertemporal plan. The index is also computable for continuous discount functions after an appropriate mapping of functions onto the (?,δ) family. The τ index thus provides a common yardstick for comparing temporal inconsistency across different functional forms.This paper was accepted by Manel Baucells, behavioral economics and decision analysis.
AB  - This paper introduces the index τ=ln?/lnδ as a measure of time inconsistency and vulnerability to self-control problems in the quasi-hyperbolic, beta-delta (?,δ) discounting model. We provide a preference foundation for τ and, consequently, a revealed preference definition of failed self-control. The τ index is independent of utility and has an intuitive interpretation as the maximum number of future selves who can disagree with the current self with respect to uniform deviations from an intertemporal plan. The index is also computable for continuous discount functions after an appropriate mapping of functions onto the (?,δ) family. The τ index thus provides a common yardstick for comparing temporal inconsistency across different functional forms.This paper was accepted by Manel Baucells, behavioral economics and decision analysis.
